{
  "response_text": "The simulation data reveals a pronounced long-term decline in mean whole milk consumption across the virtual consumer population, tracking the historical transition from 1974 to 2005. At initialization (step 0), consumption levels begin at 2654.81 units per agent, reflecting the market dominance of whole milk under the initial condition where incumbent habit strength is set to maximum (10.0). By the final time step (step 32), consumption falls to 253.104 units per agent, representing a reduction of approximately 90.5% from baseline.\n\nThe decline occurs non-linearly across three distinct phases. The first phase (steps 0-14) exhibits consistently significant decreasing trends, with the steepest decline occurring between steps 5-9 (slope: -221.111 units per step), followed by a moderated but still significant descent from steps 10-14 (slope: -38.134). By step 10, consumption has fallen to approximately 950-1000 units, and by step 14, it reaches roughly 800 units.\n\nA plateau phase emerges between steps 15-19, where the previous downward momentum temporarily stalls. During this interval, consumption oscillates between 760.0036 (step 18) and 773.9572 (step 19), with no statistically significant trend detected. This stabilization suggests a temporary equilibrium where habitual tendencies, social influence mechanisms (operating with 30% interaction probability and moderate social susceptibility of 0.2), and shifting perceptions reach a transient balance.\n\nThe third phase (steps 20-32) resumes the downward trajectory, though at varying rates. Steps 20-24 show a statistically significant but gradual decline (slope: -17.450), bringing consumption to approximately 600 units. After a brief period of stabilization around steps 25-29 (no significant trend), the final decline accelerates toward the terminal value of 253.104 units at step 32.\n\nEight inflection points at steps 5, 13, 16, 19, 24, 25, 27, and 30 mark transitions in the rate of change. The median consumption value of 816.85 units falls substantially below the mean of 1079.81 units, indicating a right-skewed distribution dominated by high initial values.\n\nSuperimposed on the downward trend, oscillatory patterns with a 15-step dominant period generate localized fluctuations concentrated around steps 2-6 and 12-14. These dynamics suggest that the macro-level transition from whole milk to skimmed and semi-skimmed varieties, driven by evolving health perceptions (initial alternative health perception: 1.69), environmental considerations (initial alternative environmental perception: 1.12), and network-based social influence, proceeded through alternating periods of rapid consumer switching, temporary stabilization, and gradual consolidation."
}

